---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Watch Folders">
  <h1>Watch Folders</h1>
  <p>
    Monitor directories for new media files and automatically register them as sources with optional analysis scheduling. Watch folders trigger source creation and analysis only — no encoding jobs are created automatically.
  </p>

  <h2>Configuration</h2>
  <p>Define watch folders in the controller YAML under the <code>watch_folders</code> key:</p>
  <pre><code>watch_folders:
  - name: incoming
    path: /mnt/nas/incoming
    windows_path: "\\\\NAS01\\incoming"
    file_patterns: ["*.mkv", "*.mp4", "*.ts"]
    poll_interval: 30s
    auto_analyze: true
    move_after_analysis: ""
    enabled: true

  - name: movies
    path: /mnt/nas/movies
    windows_path: "\\\\NAS01\\movies"
    file_patterns: ["*.mkv"]
    poll_interval: 5m
    auto_analyze: true
    enabled: true</code></pre>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Default</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>name</code></td>
        <td>string</td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Human-readable label. Used as the identifier in API calls.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>path</code></td>
        <td>string</td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Linux mount path the controller polls.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>windows_path</code></td>
        <td>string</td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Corresponding UNC path stored on source records for agent access.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>file_patterns</code></td>
        <td>string[]</td>
        <td><code>["*.mkv", "*.mp4", "*.ts", "*.avi"]</code></td>
        <td>Glob patterns to match. Empty list uses the defaults shown.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>poll_interval</code></td>
        <td>duration</td>
        <td><code>30s</code></td>
        <td>How often the folder is scanned.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>auto_analyze</code></td>
        <td>bool</td>
        <td><code>false</code></td>
        <td>When true, schedules analysis and HDR detection jobs for new files automatically.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>move_after_analysis</code></td>
        <td>string</td>
        <td><code>""</code></td>
        <td>Optional category tag applied to the source record after analysis completes.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>enabled</code></td>
        <td>bool</td>
        <td><code>false</code></td>
        <td>Controls whether polling is active. Can be toggled at runtime via the API.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>The controller starts a polling goroutine for each enabled watch folder.</li>
    <li>On each tick, the folder is scanned and files matching the glob patterns are listed.</li>
    <li>New files (not already registered as sources) trigger source creation in the database.</li>
    <li>If <code>auto_analyze</code> is enabled, analysis and HDR detection jobs are automatically scheduled.</li>
    <li>The source record stores both the Linux <code>path</code> and the <code>windows_path</code> (UNC) so agents on either platform can access the file.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>API</h2>
  <p>All watch folder endpoints require the <strong>admin</strong> role.</p>

  <h3>List watch folders</h3>
  <pre><code>GET /api/v1/watch-folders</code></pre>
  <p>Returns all configured watch folders with their current state.</p>
  <pre><code>curl -s -b cookies.txt http://localhost:8080/api/v1/watch-folders</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Response:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>&#123;
  "data": [
    &#123;
      "name": "incoming",
      "path": "/mnt/nas/incoming",
      "windows_path": "\\\\NAS01\\incoming",
      "file_patterns": ["*.mkv", "*.mp4", "*.ts"],
      "poll_interval": "30s",
      "auto_analyze": true,
      "enabled": true,
      "last_scan": null
    &#125;
  ]
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Enable or disable a watch folder</h3>
  <pre><code>PUT /api/v1/watch-folders/&#123;name&#125;/enable
PUT /api/v1/watch-folders/&#123;name&#125;/disable</code></pre>
  <p>
    Toggles the folder's enabled state in memory. The change does <strong>not</strong> persist to the YAML config file — a server restart reverts to the configured value.
  </p>
  <pre><code>curl -s -b cookies.txt -X PUT http://localhost:8080/api/v1/watch-folders/incoming/disable</code></pre>

  <h3>Trigger an immediate scan</h3>
  <pre><code>POST /api/v1/watch-folders/&#123;name&#125;/scan</code></pre>
  <p>
    Queues an immediate scan without waiting for the next poll interval. Returns <code>202 Accepted</code> and runs the scan asynchronously. The folder must be enabled.
  </p>
  <pre><code>curl -s -b cookies.txt -X POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/watch-folders/incoming/scan</code></pre>
  <p><strong>Response:</strong></p>
  <pre><code>&#123;
  "data": &#123;
    "name": "incoming",
    "status": "scan queued"
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
  <p>Returns <code>400</code> if the folder is disabled, <code>404</code> if the folder name is not found, or <code>503</code> if the watcher service is not running.</p>

  <h2>Database</h2>
  <p>
    Migration <code>030_watch_folders_rules</code> adds <code>watch_folder</code> and <code>category</code> columns to the <code>sources</code> table, allowing sources to be tagged with the watch folder they originated from.
  </p>

  <h2>UI</h2>
  <p>
    Navigate to <strong>Admin → Watch Folders</strong> to see all configured folders with their status, poll interval, and file patterns. Each folder has:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Enable/Disable</strong> toggle</li>
    <li><strong>Scan Now</strong> button for on-demand scanning</li>
    <li>File count and last scan timestamp (when available)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>New sources created by watch folders appear in the <strong>Sources</strong> list with a watch-folder badge.</p>
</DocsLayout>
